headline: FedEx shares rise after better than expected earnings
summary: STORY: Shares of FedEx jumped Friday morning after the delivery company surprised Wall Street with first-quarter results that beat expectations, fueled by strong domestic deliveries and cost-cutting.The parcel giant has leaned on efficiency measures and tighter cost controls, including parking planes, closing facilities and merging units, as it works to slash billions of dollars from its balance sheet. Overall average daily volumes rose 4% in the quarter, as strong summer holiday demand lifted U.S. parcels, countering a 3% drop in international exports.And revenue per package climbed 2%.The good news comes on the heels of FedEx ending its two-decade partnership with the U.S. Postal Service last year, a contract that had consistently weighed on earnings with high costs and thin margins.

content.title: FedEx shares rise after better than expected earnings
content.description:
STORY: Shares of FedEx jumped Friday morning after the delivery company surprised Wall Street with first-quarter results that beat expectations, fueled by strong domestic deliveries and cost-cutting.

The parcel giant has leaned on efficiency measures and tighter cost controls, including parking planes, closing facilities and merging units, as it works to slash billions of dollars from its balance sheet. 

Overall average daily volumes rose 4% in the quarter, as strong summer holiday demand lifted U.S. parcels, countering a 3% drop in international exports.

And revenue per package climbed 2%.

The good news comes on the heels of FedEx ending its two-decade partnership with the U.S. Postal Service last year, a contract that had consistently weighed on earnings with high costs and thin margins.

headline: FedEx shares rise as U.S. deliveries, cost cuts drive first-quarter results beat
summary: Shares of FedEx rose as much as 2% in early trade on Friday, after the parcel giant's first-quarter results surprised Wall Street, driven by strong domestic deliveries and cost-cutting measures that offset a tariff-induced decline in international volumes.  The company, seen as a bellwether for global trade alongside rival United Parcel Service, has leaned on efficiency measures and tighter cost controls, including parking planes, closing facilities and merging units, as it works to slash billions of dollars in costs.  Overall average daily volumes rose 4% in the quarter, as strong summer holiday demand lifted U.S. parcels, countering a 3% drop in international exports.

Trading volume in early April broke U.S. records as the market was whipsawed in the wake of U.S. President Donald Trump's tariff announcements.

headline: FedEx to Lean on Domestic Shipping as Tariffs Slow China Volume
summary: FedEx  plans to rely more on shipping within the U.S. and from markets such as Europe, as tariffs slow trade to the U.S. from China.  In the shipping company’s fiscal first quarter, export volumes declined overall, particularly to the U.S. from China.  FedEx cut capacity in trans-Pacific outbound shipments by 25%, Chief Executive  Raj Subramaniam  said on a call with analysts Thursday.
